Forrest Knutson

Mahamudra Magic

  View in app
https://youtu.be/v_X6fxdaK6g

Here's a little review of Mahamudra. Stretching lengthens the muscles, stretches the arteries, and (with a comfortable breath hold) massages the internal organs.

Lengthening the muscles causes a feeling of ease in the body before you start your meditation, making it that much easier to let go of the body before you even begin. Stretching and dilating the arteries through breath retention helps to put us in the right place to fall into the Tranquil Breath during our meditative session.

For my, "Best Meditative Setup," I'm going to:

1. Say a little prayer to connect with the Divine, setting my intention

2. Do three sets of Mahamudra stretching

3. Practice one (or more) rounds of Navi Kriya

4. Practice the Long Breathing of HRV-Resonance

5. Practice some OM Japa in the chakras to clean the way

6. Let go and enjoy the good effects, which is the Paravastha state

Beautiful, right? Now, before I get up from my meditation, especially if I've gone fairly deep, the Kriya Yogis recommend I do one more stretch to harmonize the body. I remember sitting in front of Ashokji, mentally thinking, "Why do I have to stretch again? I already stretched in the beginning." I didn't say it out loud, because that would be a little embarrassing. Well, he read my mind and answered, "We stretch again so you don't get up and trip over your own feet!" Hahaha!

Blissings dear family!
